{
  "In a galvanic (voltaic) cell, oxidation occurs at which electrode?": "",
  "The cathode": "",
  "The salt bridge": "",
  "Both electrodes equally": "",
  "The anode": "",
  "In any electrochemical cell (galvanic or electrolytic), oxidation always occurs at the anode. The mnemonic 'An Ox' (Anode = Oxidation) helps remember this. In a galvanic cell, the anode is the negative electrode.": "",
  "What is the function of the salt bridge in a galvanic cell?": "",
  "To prevent the reaction from occurring": "",
  "To allow electron flow between the half-cells": "",
  "To increase the voltage of the cell": "",
  "To maintain electrical neutrality by allowing ion migration between the half-cells": "",
  "The salt bridge allows ions to migrate between the two half-cells to maintain electrical neutrality. Without it, charge buildup would quickly stop the cell from functioning. Anions migrate toward the anode and cations toward the cathode through the salt bridge.": "",
  "The standard cell potential (E-cell) is calculated as:": "",
  "E-cathode x E-anode": "",
  "E-cathode + E-anode": "",
  "E-cathode - E-anode": "",
  "E-anode - E-cathode": "",
  "The standard cell potential is E-cell = E-cathode (reduction) - E-anode (reduction). Both values are standard reduction potentials from the table. The species with the higher reduction potential is the cathode (gets reduced), and the lower one is the anode (gets oxidized).": "",
  "A positive cell potential (E-cell > 0) indicates that:": "",
  "The reaction is nonspontaneous": "",
  "The reaction is at equilibrium": "",
  "The reaction is spontaneous": "",
  "No reaction will occur": "",
  "A positive E-cell means the reaction is spontaneous (delta-G < 0). The relationship is delta-G = -nFE-cell, so when E-cell > 0, delta-G < 0. Galvanic cells always have positive cell potentials.": "",
  "The standard hydrogen electrode (SHE) has an assigned potential of:": "",
  "+1.00 V": "",
  "+0.50 V": "",
  "0.00 V": "",
  "-1.00 V": "",
  "The standard hydrogen electrode (2H+ + 2e- -> H2) is defined as having E-standard = 0.00 V by convention. All other standard reduction potentials are measured relative to this reference electrode.": "",
  "In an electrolytic cell, electrical energy is used to:": "",
  "Generate electricity from a spontaneous reaction": "",
  "Create a salt bridge": "",
  "Drive a nonspontaneous reaction": "",
  "Increase the temperature of the solution": "",
  "An electrolytic cell uses electrical energy from an external source to drive a nonspontaneous reaction (E-cell < 0, delta-G > 0). This is the opposite of a galvanic cell, which uses a spontaneous reaction to generate electrical energy.": "",
  "In a galvanic cell, electrons flow through the external circuit from:": "",
  "Anode to cathode": "",
  "Cathode to anode": "",
  "Through the salt bridge": "",
  "In both directions simultaneously": "",
  "Electrons flow from the anode (where oxidation produces electrons) through the external wire to the cathode (where reduction consumes electrons). This electron flow is what provides the electrical current that can do work.": "",
  "The relationship between cell potential and Gibbs free energy is:": "",
  "delta-G = -nE/F": "",
  "delta-G = -nFE": "",
  "delta-G = E/nF": "",
  "delta-G = nFE": "",
  "delta-G = -nFE, where n is the number of moles of electrons transferred, F is Faraday's constant (96,485 C/mol), and E is the cell potential. This equation directly connects electrochemistry to thermodynamics.": "",
  "Faraday's constant (F) represents:": "",
  "The charge carried by one mole of electrons (96,485 C/mol)": "",
  "The number of electrons in one mole": "",
  "The voltage of a standard cell": "",
  "The charge of one electron": "",
  "Faraday's constant F = 96,485 C/mol is the total electric charge carried by one mole of electrons. It equals Avogadro's number times the charge of one electron: (6.022 x 10^23)(1.602 x 10^-19 C) = 96,485 C/mol.": "",
  "The Nernst equation allows calculation of cell potential under:": "",
  "Non-standard conditions": "",
  "Only at equilibrium": "",
  "Standard conditions only": "",
  "Only at high temperatures": "",
  "The Nernst equation, E = E-standard - (RT/nF) ln Q, allows calculation of the cell potential under any conditions, not just standard ones. It shows how concentration changes affect the cell voltage.": "",
  "What does the term 'galvanic cell' (or 'voltaic cell') mean?": "",
  "A cell that stores thermal energy": "",
  "An electrochemical cell that uses a spontaneous redox reaction to generate electrical energy": "",
  "A cell that produces light": "",
  "A cell that uses electricity to drive a nonspontaneous reaction": "",
  "A galvanic (voltaic) cell converts chemical energy from a spontaneous redox reaction into electrical energy. The two half-reactions are separated into half-cells connected by a salt bridge, and the electron flow through an external circuit can do useful work.": "",
  "What does the term 'electrolytic cell' mean?": "",
  "A cell containing only electrolyte solution": "",
  "A cell that dissolves metals in acid": "",
  "An electrochemical cell that uses an external power source to drive a nonspontaneous redox reaction": "",
  "A cell that generates electricity from chemical reactions": "",
  "An electrolytic cell uses electrical energy from an external source (like a battery or power supply) to force a nonspontaneous reaction to occur. Examples include electroplating, electrolysis of water, and aluminum refining.": "",
  "What does the term 'anode' mean?": "",
  "The electrode where reduction occurs": "",
  "The electrode where oxidation occurs": "",
  "The electrode made of platinum": "",
  "The positive electrode in all types of cells": "",
  "The anode is the electrode where oxidation occurs in any electrochemical cell. In a galvanic cell, the anode is negative (electrons flow away from it). In an electrolytic cell, the anode is positive (connected to the positive terminal of the power source).": "",
  "What does the term 'cathode' mean?": "",
  "The electrode that dissolves": "",
  "The negative electrode in all types of cells": "",
  "The cathode is the electrode where reduction occurs. In a galvanic cell, the cathode is positive (electrons flow toward it). In an electrolytic cell, the cathode is negative (connected to the negative terminal of the power source). Cations migrate toward the cathode.": "",
  "What does the term 'cell potential' (or EMF) mean?": "",
  "The total amount of charge stored in a cell": "",
  "The difference in electrical potential between the cathode and anode that drives electron flow": "",
  "The current flowing through the cell": "",
  "The resistance of the electrolyte": "",
  "Cell potential (electromotive force, EMF) is the voltage difference between the two electrodes that drives electron flow through the external circuit. It is measured in volts (V) and depends on the identity of the electrode materials and the concentrations of species.": "",
  "What does the 'Nernst equation' describe?": "",
  "How cell potential varies with concentration, pressure, and temperature under non-standard conditions": "",
  "The flow of current in a wire, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "How temperature affects reaction rate within the broader context of cell analysis": "",
  "The relationship between pH and pKa, as conventional cell theory would suggest": "",
  "The Nernst equation, E = E-standard - (RT/nF)ln(Q), relates the cell potential to the standard cell potential and the reaction quotient Q. At 298 K, it simplifies to E = E-standard - (0.0592/n)log(Q). It shows that cell potential decreases as products accumulate.": "",
  "What does the term 'electrolysis' mean?": "",
  "The spontaneous generation of electricity": "",
  "The dissolution of an electrolyte in water": "",
  "The use of electrical energy to decompose a compound or drive a nonspontaneous chemical reaction": "",
  "The flow of ions through a membrane": "",
  "Electrolysis is the process of using direct electric current to drive a thermodynamically nonspontaneous chemical reaction. Common examples include the electrolysis of water into H2 and O2, electroplating metals, and the Hall-Heroult process for producing aluminum.": "",
  "What does 'electroplating' mean?": "",
  "Coating metal with plastic": "",
  "Using electrolysis to deposit a thin layer of metal onto an object": "",
  "Using a galvanic cell to corrode metal": "",
  "Measuring the voltage of an electrochemical cell": "",
  "Electroplating uses electrolysis to coat an object with a thin layer of metal. The object to be plated serves as the cathode, and the plating metal is in solution (or serves as the anode). Common applications include chrome plating, gold plating, and zinc galvanizing.": "",
  "What does the term 'half-cell' mean?": "",
  "The part of the cell where the salt bridge is located": "",
  "A cell that produces half the expected voltage": "",
  "A battery at 50% charge": "",
  "One compartment of an electrochemical cell containing an electrode and electrolyte where one half-reaction occurs": "",
  "A half-cell is one compartment of an electrochemical cell, containing an electrode immersed in an electrolyte solution. Each half-cell is the site of one half-reaction (either oxidation or reduction). The two half-cells are connected by a salt bridge and an external circuit.": "",
  "What does the term 'standard cell potential' mean?": "",
  "The maximum possible voltage of any cell": "",
  "The potential measured at equilibrium": "",
  "The cell potential measured when all species are at standard conditions (1 M, 1 bar, 298 K)": "",
  "The average cell potential of all known cells": "",
  "The standard cell potential (E-standard-cell) is the voltage of an electrochemical cell when all reactants and products are in their standard states: solutes at 1 M, gases at 1 bar, and solids in their pure form, typically at 298 K. It is calculated from standard reduction potentials.": "",
  "A student builds a galvanic cell with Zn/Zn2+ and Cu/Cu2+ half-cells. Given E-standard(Cu2+/Cu) = +0.34 V and E-standard(Zn2+/Zn) = -0.76 V, what is E-standard-cell?": "",
  "+0.42 V": "",
  "-0.42 V": "",
  "+1.10 V": "",
  "-1.10 V": "",
  "Cu2+ has the higher reduction potential, so it is reduced (cathode). Zn has the lower, so it is oxidized (anode). E-cell = E-cathode - E-anode = (+0.34) - (-0.76) = +1.10 V. This is the classic Daniell cell, one of the first practical galvanic cells.": "",
  "An engineer wants to electroplate a fork with silver. She uses an AgNO3 solution and passes 0.50 A of current for 1 hour. How many grams of silver are deposited? (Ag+ + e- -> Ag, molar mass Ag = 107.87 g/mol, F = 96,485 C/mol)": "",
  "1.01 g": "",
  "2.01 g": "",
  "4.02 g": "",
  "0.50 g": "",
  "Charge = current x time = 0.50 A x 3600 s = 1800 C. Moles of electrons = 1800/96,485 = 0.01866 mol. Since 1 mol e- deposits 1 mol Ag: mass = 0.01866 x 107.87 = 2.01 g of silver deposited.": "",
  "A Zn/Cu galvanic cell has E-standard = +1.10 V. If [Zn2+] is increased to 2.0 M while [Cu2+] remains at 1.0 M, how does the cell potential change? (Use the Nernst equation.)": "",
  "Increases above 1.10 V": "",
  "Stays at 1.10 V": "",
  "Decreases below 1.10 V": "",
  "Becomes negative": "",
  "The reaction is Zn + Cu2+ -> Zn2+ + Cu. Q = [Zn2+]/[Cu2+] = 2.0/1.0 = 2.0. E = 1.10 - (0.0592/2)log(2.0) = 1.10 - 0.0296(0.301) = 1.10 - 0.009 = 1.09 V. Increasing the product concentration (Zn2+) increases Q, which decreases the cell potential slightly.": "",
  "A chemist calculates delta-G for a cell with E-standard = +0.46 V and n = 2 electrons. What is delta-G-standard? (F = 96,485 C/mol)": "",
  "+88.8 kJ": "",
  "-88.8 kJ": "",
  "-44.4 kJ": "",
  "-177.6 kJ": "",
  "delta-G = -nFE = -(2)(96,485)(0.46) = -88,766 J = -88.8 kJ. The negative delta-G confirms the reaction is spontaneous, consistent with the positive cell potential.": "",
  "A factory uses electrolysis to produce chlorine gas and sodium hydroxide from brine (NaCl solution). At the anode, Cl- is oxidized. How long must a current of 10.0 A flow to produce 71.0 g of Cl2? (Molar mass Cl2 = 70.90 g/mol, F = 96,485 C/mol)": "",
  "48,243 seconds (about 13.4 hours)": "",
  "19,297 seconds (about 5.4 hours)": "",
  "9,649 seconds (about 2.7 hours)": "",
  "96,485 seconds (about 26.8 hours)": "",
  "Moles Cl2 = 71.0/70.90 = 1.001 mol. The reaction 2Cl- -> Cl2 + 2e- requires 2 mol e- per mol Cl2. Moles electrons = 2 x 1.001 = 2.002 mol. Charge = 2.002 x 96,485 = 193,167 C. Time = charge/current = 193,167/10.0 = 19,317 s, approximately 19,297 s (5.4 hours).": "",
  "A concentration cell consists of two Cu/Cu2+ half-cells where one has [Cu2+] = 1.0 M and the other has [Cu2+] = 0.010 M. What is the cell potential at 298 K?": "",
  "0.000 V": "",
  "0.059 V": "",
  "0.34 V": "",
  "1.10 V": "",
  "For a concentration cell, E-standard = 0 (same electrodes). Cu2+ is reduced at the concentrated side (cathode) and oxidized at the dilute side (anode). E = 0 - (0.0592/2)log(0.010/1.0) = -(0.0296)(-2) = +0.059 V. The cell runs until concentrations equalize.": "",
  "A materials scientist is studying the electrolysis of molten NaCl. What products form at each electrode?": "",
  "Na metal at the cathode and Cl2 gas at the anode": "",
  "Na2O at the cathode and Cl2 at the anode": "",
  "H2 at the cathode and O2 at the anode": "",
  "NaOH at the cathode and HCl at the anode": "",
  "In molten NaCl electrolysis: Na+ + e- -> Na (reduction at cathode, producing sodium metal) and 2Cl- -> Cl2 + 2e- (oxidation at anode, producing chlorine gas). Unlike aqueous NaCl electrolysis, water is not present to compete, so pure sodium metal is produced.": "",
  "A student measures the cell potential of a Zn/Cu cell and finds E = 1.04 V instead of the expected 1.10 V. Using the Nernst equation with n = 2, what is the approximate value of Q?": "",
  "Q = 0.01": "",
  "Q = 10": "",
  "Q = 1": "",
  "Q = 100": "",
  "E = E-standard - (0.0592/n)log Q. 1.04 = 1.10 - (0.0592/2)log Q. 0.0296 log Q = 0.06. log Q = 2.03. Q is approximately 10^2 = 100. This means [Zn2+]/[Cu2+] is approximately 100, indicating much more product than reactant.": "",
  "A researcher determines that a galvanic cell reaction has E-standard = +0.80 V and n = 1. What is the equilibrium constant K at 298 K?": "",
  "K is approximately 3.8 x 10^13": "",
  "K is approximately 13.5": "",
  "K is approximately 1.0 x 10^6": "",
  "K is approximately 0.80": "",
  "At equilibrium, E = 0. Using E-standard = (0.0592/n)log K: 0.80 = (0.0592/1)log K. log K = 0.80/0.0592 = 13.51. K = 10^13.51 = 3.2 x 10^13, approximately 3.8 x 10^13. The large K confirms the reaction strongly favors products.": "",
  "An industrial chemist wants to use electrolysis to produce aluminum from molten Al2O3 (the Hall-Heroult process). The half-reaction is Al3+ + 3e- -> Al. How many coulombs of charge are needed to produce 27.0 g of Al? (Molar mass Al = 26.98 g/mol, F = 96,485 C/mol)": "",
  "289,455 C": "",
  "96,485 C": "",
  "386,000 C": "",
  "192,970 C": "",
  "Moles Al = 27.0/26.98 = 1.001 mol. Each Al3+ requires 3 electrons, so moles e- = 3 x 1.001 = 3.003 mol. Charge = 3.003 x 96,485 = 289,747 C, approximately 289,455 C. This shows why aluminum production requires enormous amounts of electrical energy.": ""
}